      <div xml:id="NA139-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu talaivaṉ viṉaimuṟṟi vantu paḷḷiyiṭattaṉākap peyta maḻaiyai vāḻttiyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is ho HE praised the rain that fell while he was in bed, having come back after the work had been accomplished.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA139">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            ulakiṟ kāṇi yākap palartoḻap</l>
<l>            palavayi ṉilaiiya kuṉṟiṟ kōṭutō</l>
<l>            ṟēyiṉai yuraiiyarō peruṅkali yeḻili</l>
<l>            paṭumalai niṉṟa nalyāḻ vaṭinaram</l>
<l>            peḻīi yaṉṉa yuṟaiyiṉai muḻaviṉ </l>
<l>            maṇṇār kaṇṇi ṉimmeṉa vimirum</l>
<l>            vaṇarntoli kūntaṉ māa yōḷoṭu</l>
<l>            puṇarntiṉitu nukarnta cāra ṉallūr</l>
<l>            viravumala rutira vīci</l>
<l>            yiravuppeyal poḻinta vutavi yōyē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>You who seem to be</l>
<l rend="indent">on every hill peak where you remained in many places</l>
<l rend="indent2">for many to worship as a support to the world,</l>
<l rend="indent3">may you talk, o big bustling cloud,</l>
<l>you who have been of help when rain flowed [from you] at night,</l>
<l rend="indent">throwing [water] so that the mixed blossoms dropped off</l>
<l rend="indent2">on the good village on the slope that enjoyed<note place="foot">Here we have to read an ellipsis, since it is presumably not the slope or the village, but the HE himself who has enjoyed HER.</note> something sweet,</l>
<l rend="indent3">[me] being united with the dark one with tresses that sprout curly,</l>
<l rend="indent2">humming<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">imirum</term>: if the cloud is still the subject (which undoubtedly must be the case), a <term xml:lang="ta">peyareccam</term> cannot be construed here; we expect an absolutive, parallel to <term xml:lang="ta">vīci</term>. We might try to read a further description of their being together, that is, the real sounding of drums ("when..."), but this is impossible, because both <term xml:lang="ta">kaṇṇiṉ</term> and <term xml:lang="ta">muḻaviṉ</term> are marked as an oblique and thus neither can be subject of <term xml:lang="ta">imirum</term>.</note> 'im' like the eye full of paste of the drum,</l>
<l>you who reside<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">uṟaiyiṉai</term> must be an appellative noun, either from uṟai "residence" or from <term xml:lang="ta">uṟai</term> "drop, rain".</note> as if awakening</l>
<l rend="indent">the practised strings of the good lute persisting in the Paṭumalai melody.</l>
        </lg>
         </div>
